}

{
  "query": "What are the potential benefits and harms of controlling fish populations to protect amphibians?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, controlling fish populations to protect amphibians shows several potential benefits but also some harms. Benefits include: removing fish by catching significantly increased abundance of salamanders or frogs and increased recruitment, survival and population growth rate of cascades frog (Action 827); eliminating fish using rotenone increased numbers of amphibian species, abundance and recruitment or newt populations (Action 828); draining ponds to eliminate fish increased numbers of amphibian species and increased breeding success of frog or newt species (Action 826); and using barriers to exclude fish increased weight gain of axolotls (Action 829). However, harms were also documented: fish control using rotenone resulted in many frogs dying and a small number of newts showing symptoms of negative effects (Action 828); fish control had no significant effect on great crested newt populations and fish remained or returned within a few years (Action 827); and fish control did not increase green toad breeding success and fish were soon reintroduced (Action 827).",
  "action_ids": [
