  "relevant_summary": "Studies have documented both benefits and negative impacts of releasing captive-bred or head-started toads into the wild. Benefits include successful population establishment, with captive-bred toads establishing populations at 70% of sites in some studies, and head-started amphibians successfully establishing breeding populations or increasing existing populations in 6 of 10 studies. Head-started amphibians showed successful metamorphosis, survival through seasons, and breeding in 9 of 10 studies, with better survival to metamorphosis and larger size at metamorphosis compared to wild animals in some cases.\n\nHowever, significant negative impacts have also been documented. Survival rates can be very low, with one study finding only 25% of released captive-bred Puerto Rican crested toads survived, with 25% predated within two days of release. Adult survival over four years was only 1-17% in one study. Genetic diversity can be reduced in captive-bred reintroduced populations compared to wild populations. Some programs failed to establish breeding populations or prevent population declines despite head-starting efforts. Overall, a review found that only 41% of release programs showed evidence of breeding in the wild for multiple generations, with 29% showing some evidence of breeding and 12% showing only survival following release.",
