{
  "query": "To manage chytridiomycosis in captive amphibians, what are the most and least beneficial treatment strategies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from action documents, the most beneficial treatment strategies for managing chytridiomycosis in captive amphibians are antifungal treatment and temperature treatment. Antifungal treatment, particularly itraconazole, was effective at curing amphibians of chytridiomycosis in 12 of 16 studies, including six of eight studies specifically testing itraconazole (Action ID: 882). However, six studies found that specific fungicides caused death or other negative side effects in amphibians. Temperature treatment showed high effectiveness, with four of five studies finding that increasing enclosure or water temperature to 30-37\u00b0C for over 16 hours cured frogs and toads of chytridiomycosis (Action ID: 770).\n\nThe least beneficial treatment strategies are antifungal skin bacteria or peptides and antibacterial treatments. Three of four studies found that adding antifungal bacteria to the skin of salamanders or frogs exposed to chytrid fungus did not reduce infection rate or death, and treatment with antimicrobial skin peptides did not significantly increase survival of common toads (Action ID: 764). Antibacterial treatments showed mixed results, with trimethoprim-sulfadiazine increasing survival time but not curing blue-and-yellow poison dart frogs of chytridiomycosis (Action ID: 763).",
